My scenario is that I have a setting (`window.title`) which I want to provide IntelliSense for because the value of this setting can have variables (e.g. `$(activeFile)`).

I tried two different strategies:

1. from the main side: this is https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/issues/20028

2. do it proper and from the `config-editing` extension. however I fail to provide a completion item provider for `**/settings.json` that gets triggered. In the [activate](https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/blob/master/extensions/configuration-editing/src/extension.ts#L16) method I do:

```typescript
context.subscriptions.push(registerSettingsCompletions());
```

Which is implemented as:

```typescript
function registerSettingsCompletions(): vscode.Disposable {
	return vscode.languages.registerCompletionItemProvider({ pattern: '**/settings.json' }, {

		provideCompletionItems(document, position, token) {
			const location = getLocation(document.getText(), document.offsetAt(position));
			console.log("location");
			if (location.path[1] === 'window.title') {

				const range = document.getWordRangeAtPosition(position) || new vscode.Range(position, position);
				return Promise.resolve([newCompletionItem('huhu', range)]);
			}
		}
	});
}
```

But again nothing. Not even the `console.log` is printed so I think my contribution is not even being called when I press `Ctrl+Space` in settings.

My scenario is that I have a setting (`window.title`) which I want to provide IntelliSense for because the value of this setting can have variables (e.g. `$(activeFile)`).

I tried two different strategies:

1. from the main side, add a `JSONWorkerContribution` to our JSON server and implement `collectValueCompletions`, e.g. like this:

```typescript
public collectValueCompletions(resource: string, location: JSONPath, currentKey: string, result: CompletionsCollector): Thenable<any> {
    if (this.isSettingsFile(resource) && location.length === 1 && location[0] === 'window.title') {
        result.add({ kind: CompletionItemKind.Value, label: localize('trueLabel', "$(activeFile)"), filterText: 'true', insertText: 'true', documentation: localize('activeFileDescription', "Enable activeFile.") });
    }

    return null;
} 
```

=> I am not getting a completion when I do so

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/900690/22643073/54686c04-ec5d-11e6-9db2-36161089cb7e.png)

2. do it proper and from the `config-editing` extension: this is https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/issues/20030

- VSCode Version: 1.8.1 (commit ee428b0)
- OS Version: Ubuntu 16.04.1

The code:
```js
let p1 = new Promise(function(resolve, reject) {
    setTimeout(resolve, 100, 'OK!!!');
});
let p2 = new Promise(function(resolve, reject) {
    setTimeout(reject, 300, new Error('Operation timed out'));
});

Promise.race([p3, p2]).then(function(result) {
    console.log('Got result: %s', result);
}, function (error) {
    console.log('Got error: %s', error.message);
});
```

(It's almost the same as the example in Mozilla Develpoer Network)

This code is expected to give output `Got result: OK!!!`, and it works fine in Node.js from command line. Node.js will not give any warnings.

However, when debugging this snippet in VS Code, execution will be interrupted for the timed-out error. It's already catched by the `race` sentence, so I wonder if this should not happen.
